---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "WebApplication",
      "name": "QR Code Generator — Free Online QR Maker",
      "url": "https://siliconbased.dev/qr-code-generator",
      "description": "Free QR code generator. Create QR codes for URLs, text, email, phone, WiFi, and vCard contacts. Customize size, colors, and error correction. Download as PNG.",
      "applicationCategory": "UtilitiesApplication",
      "operatingSystem": "Any",
      "offers": {
        "@type": "Offer",
        "price": "0",
        "priceCurrency": "USD"
      },
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "GAB Ventures",
        "url": "https://gab.ae"
      }
    },
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is a QR code?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A QR (Quick Response) code is a two-dimensional barcode that stores data in a grid of black and white squares. It was invented in 1994 by Denso Wave for tracking automotive parts and has since become ubiquitous for sharing URLs, contact information, WiFi credentials, and more. QR codes can be scanned by any smartphone camera."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are QR code error correction levels?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "QR codes have four error correction levels: L (Low, ~7% recovery), M (Medium, ~15% recovery), Q (Quartile, ~25% recovery), and H (High, ~30% recovery). Higher error correction means the code can still be read even if partially damaged or obscured, but it also makes the QR code denser with more modules."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What data types can a QR code encode?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "QR codes can encode plain text, URLs, email addresses (mailto: format), phone numbers (tel: format), WiFi network credentials (SSID, password, encryption type), vCard contact information (name, phone, email, organization), SMS messages, calendar events, and geographic coordinates. Most smartphones automatically recognize and act on these formats."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How far away can a QR code be scanned?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The scan distance depends on the QR code's physical size and the number of modules. A general rule is that the scan distance is roughly 10 times the QR code's width. A 2.5 cm (1 inch) QR code can be scanned from about 25 cm (10 inches) away, while a 30 cm (12 inch) code can be scanned from about 3 meters (10 feet)."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I customize the colors of a QR code?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, you can change the foreground and background colors of a QR code. However, maintain high contrast between the two colors for reliable scanning. Dark foreground on light background works best. Avoid using colors that are too similar in luminance, and never invert the colors (light modules on dark background) as many scanners cannot read inverted codes."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};

const htmlBody = `<div class="page-content">
<div style="background:rgba(129,140,248,0.08);border:1px solid rgba(129,140,248,0.2);border-radius:12px;padding:1rem 1.5rem;font-size:0.88rem;color:var(--text-secondary);line-height:1.6;margin-bottom:1rem;">
  📱 <strong style="color:#818cf8;">QR code usage grew 443% since 2020 — restaurants, payments, and business cards all went QR.</strong> Generate unlimited codes for URLs, WiFi, contacts, and more. Runs entirely in your browser — no data sent to any server. <a href="https://gab.ae/news/lloyds-bank-it-glitch-half-million-customers-data-exposed-2026" style="color:#818cf8;">Why privacy-first tools matter →</a>
</div>
<div class="hero">
  <h1>QR Code Generator</h1>
  <p>Generate QR codes for URLs, text, email, phone, WiFi, and contacts. Customize and download as PNG.</p>
</div>

<div class="main">

  <!-- Data Type Selector -->
  <div class="type-tabs" id="typeTabs">
    <button class="type-tab active" data-type="url">URL</button>
    <button class="type-tab" data-type="text">Text</button>
    <button class="type-tab" data-type="email">Email</button>
    <button class="type-tab" data-type="phone">Phone</button>
    <button class="type-tab" data-type="wifi">WiFi</button>
    <button class="type-tab" data-type="vcard">vCard</button>
  </div>

  <!-- Input Forms -->
  <div class="input-section">
    <div class="input-form active" id="form-url">
      <label>URL</label>
      <input type="url" id="inputUrl" placeholder="https://example.com" value="https://siliconbased.dev" class="text-input">
    </div>
    <div class="input-form" id="form-text">
      <label>Text</label>
      <textarea id="inputText" placeholder="Enter any text..." class="text-input textarea-input" rows="3"></textarea>
    </div>
    <div class="input-form" id="form-email">
      <label>Email Address</label>
      <input type="email" id="inputEmail" placeholder="name@example.com" class="text-input">
      <label>Subject (optional)</label>
      <input type="text" id="inputEmailSubject" placeholder="Email subject" class="text-input">
      <label>Body (optional)</label>
      <textarea id="inputEmailBody" placeholder="Email body..." class="text-input textarea-input" rows="2"></textarea>
    </div>
    <div class="input-form" id="form-phone">
      <label>Phone Number</label>
      <input type="tel" id="inputPhone" placeholder="+1234567890" class="text-input">
    </div>
    <div class="input-form" id="form-wifi">
      <label>Network Name (SSID)</label>
      <input type="text" id="inputWifiSsid" placeholder="MyNetwork" class="text-input">
      <label>Password</label>
      <input type="text" id="inputWifiPass" placeholder="Password" class="text-input">
      <label>Encryption</label>
      <select id="inputWifiEnc" class="text-input">
        <option value="WPA">WPA/WPA2</option>
        <option value="WEP">WEP</option>
        <option value="nopass">None</option>
      </select>
      <label class="checkbox-label"><input type="checkbox" id="inputWifiHidden"> Hidden Network</label>
    </div>
    <div class="input-form" id="form-vcard">
      <div class="vcard-grid">
        <div><label>First Name</label><input type="text" id="inputVcardFn" placeholder="John" class="text-input"></div>
        <div><label>Last Name</label><input type="text" id="inputVcardLn" placeholder="Doe" class="text-input"></div>
        <div><label>Phone</label><input type="tel" id="inputVcardPhone" placeholder="+1234567890" class="text-input"></div>
        <div><label>Email</label><input type="email" id="inputVcardEmail" placeholder="john@example.com" class="text-input"></div>
        <div><label>Organization</label><input type="text" id="inputVcardOrg" placeholder="Company Inc." class="text-input"></div>
        <div><label>Title</label><input type="text" id="inputVcardTitle" placeholder="Software Engineer" class="text-input"></div>
        <div style="grid-column: 1 / -1;"><label>Website</label><input type="url" id="inputVcardUrl" placeholder="https://example.com" class="text-input"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Customization -->
  <div class="options-row">
    <div class="option-group">
      <label>Size</label>
      <div class="range-row">
        <input type="range" id="optSize" min="128" max="512" value="256" step="8" class="range-input">
        <span class="range-val" id="optSizeVal">256px</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="option-group">
      <label>Error Correction</label>
      <select id="optEc" class="text-input select-sm">
        <option value="M" selected>M — Medium (15%)</option>
        <option value="L">L — Low (7%)</option>
        <option value="Q">Q — Quartile (25%)</option>
        <option value="H">H — High (30%)</option>
      </select>
    </div>
    <div class="option-group">
      <label>Foreground</label>
      <div class="color-row">
        <input type="color" id="optFg" value="#000000" class="color-picker-input">
        <input type="text" id="optFgText" value="#000000" class="text-input color-text-sm">
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="option-group">
      <label>Background</label>
      <div class="color-row">
        <input type="color" id="optBg" value="#ffffff" class="color-picker-input">
        <input type="text" id="optBgText" value="#ffffff" class="text-input color-text-sm">
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Generate Button -->
  <button class="generate-btn" id="generateBtn">Generate QR Code</button>

  <!-- Output -->
  <div class="output-section" id="outputSection" style="display:none;">
    <div class="output-card">
      <canvas id="qrCanvas"></canvas>
      <button class="download-btn" id="downloadBtn">Download PNG</button>
    </div>
    <div class="info-card">
      <h3>Encoded Data</h3>
      <div class="info-row"><span class="info-label">Type</span><span class="info-value" id="infoType">—</span></div>
      <div class="info-row"><span class="info-label">Data Length</span><span class="info-value" id="infoLength">—</span></div>
      <div class="info-row"><span class="info-label">Error Correction</span><span class="info-value" id="infoEc">—</span></div>
      <div class="info-row"><span class="info-label">QR Version</span><span class="info-value" id="infoVersion">—</span></div>
      <div class="info-row"><span class="info-label">Module Count</span><span class="info-value" id="infoModules">—</span></div>
      <div class="info-row"><span class="info-label">Est. Scan Distance</span><span class="info-value" id="infoDistance">—</span></div>
      <div class="info-data-wrap">
        <h4>Raw Data</h4>
        <pre class="info-raw" id="infoRaw"></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- SEO Content + FAQ -->
  <div class="seo-content">
    <h2>What is a QR Code Generator?</h2>
    <p>A QR code generator creates two-dimensional barcodes that encode data in a matrix of dark and light modules. QR codes can store URLs, plain text, contact information, WiFi credentials, and more. This tool generates QR codes entirely in your browser — no data is sent to any server, ensuring complete privacy.</p>

    <h2>Understanding QR Code Structure</h2>
    <p>Every QR code contains several key components: finder patterns (the three large squares in the corners) for orientation detection, alignment patterns for distortion correction, timing patterns to establish the grid, format information encoding the error correction level, and the data region containing the actual encoded information. The "version" of a QR code (1–40) determines its size, from 21×21 modules (version 1) to 177×177 modules (version 40).</p>

    <h2>Error Correction Levels Explained</h2>
    <p>QR codes use Reed-Solomon error correction to remain scannable even when partially damaged. There are four levels:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>L (Low):</strong> ~7% of data can be restored. Smallest code size, best for clean environments.</li>
      <li><strong>M (Medium):</strong> ~15% recovery. Good balance for most uses — the default choice.</li>
      <li><strong>Q (Quartile):</strong> ~25% recovery. Recommended for printed materials that may get worn.</li>
      <li><strong>H (High):</strong> ~30% recovery. Best for harsh environments or when adding a logo overlay.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Best Practices for QR Codes</h2>
    <p>Keep the data short — shorter data means fewer modules and easier scanning. Use high contrast colors (dark foreground, light background). Never invert colors. For print, ensure the QR code is at least 2 cm × 2 cm. Test the code with multiple scanner apps before distributing. Use error correction level M or higher for printed materials.</p>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div style="margin-top: 24px;">
      <h3 style="margin: 16px 0 8px; font-size: 1.1rem; color: #e0e0e0;">What is a QR code?</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">A QR (Quick Response) code is a 2D barcode that stores data in a grid of black and white squares. Invented in 1994, it can be scanned by any smartphone camera to quickly access URLs, contacts, and more.</p>

      <h3 style="margin: 16px 0 8px; font-size: 1.1rem; color: #e0e0e0;">What are error correction levels?</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">QR codes have four levels: L (7% recovery), M (15%), Q (25%), and H (30%). Higher levels make codes readable even when partially damaged, but increase density.</p>

      <h3 style="margin: 16px 0 8px; font-size: 1.1rem; color: #e0e0e0;">What data types can QR codes encode?</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">QR codes can encode URLs, plain text, email addresses, phone numbers, WiFi credentials, vCard contacts, SMS messages, calendar events, and geographic coordinates.</p>

      <h3 style="margin: 16px 0 8px; font-size: 1.1rem; color: #e0e0e0;">How far away can a QR code be scanned?</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">Scan distance is roughly 10× the code's width. A 2.5 cm code scans from ~25 cm away; a 30 cm code from ~3 meters.</p>

      <h3 style="margin: 16px 0 8px; font-size: 1.1rem; color: #e0e0e0;">Can I customize QR code colors?</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">Yes, but maintain high contrast between foreground and background. Dark on light works best. Avoid inverted or low-contrast colors as many scanners won't read them.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Related Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/color-contrast-checker">Color Contrast Checker</a> — Check WCAG contrast compliance for your QR code colors.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

</div>
</div>`;

